    Having watched 21 episodes prior to writing this review, I have to say Shin Sekai Yori is perhaps the most intelligent anime series I have ever watched. The premise of the story, the interactions between races, the policies set into place, and the rationale and philosophy behind them are both believable and well thought out. Furthermore, the actual execution of the story is superb; they will drop frequent hints and include much foreshadowing, allowing you to draw your own conclusions, yet they still manage to completely surprise you. Note that the first few episodes do not begin in medias res, or have an explosive introduction\
          \
        into a new world like most modern anime do; rather, you experience events as the children do – learning more about the world around them and gradually realizing that something is horribly wrong with the society they live in. \
Story: 10\
This anime is heavily reliant on its plot in order to engage you. It begins with an introduction to the world of the children: The 66th district of Kamisu, set 1000 years in the future, holds many secrets from the children, and is a powder keg for disaster. The story is extremely well told: there are no actual filler episodes, and after the first few episodes about the children’s daily lives, the story will begin to snowball in intensity and tension.\
Art: 9\
The art itself is superb: it creates a beautiful backdrop for Kimisu’s seemingly utopian society, contrasted with the monster rats’ rather disgusting design. The design of the monster rats will play into the interactions between the two races. The humans are attractive, but the designs are not distinctive or bold – they are, after all, normal people in Kamisu. \
As opposed to the art, the animation is good, but not amazing. This is not Kyoto Animation spending a huge budget on animating Haruhi’s guitar playing, or Joshiraku’s 6 seconds of amazing animation. However, while the “wow” moments were few, there were no noticeable moments where the animation was actually lacking. I still wish A-1 pictures had been given more money for the animation though: the result would have been simply astounding, especially given the cantus powers.\
Sound: 9\
The music provided the mood in during times of tension and during particularly traumatic/dramatic moments. While not as distinctive or engaging as Kanno Yoko’s music in Sakamichi no Apollon or Cowboy Bebop, the music in Shin Sekai Yori was definitely very good. Each of the characters are well voiced, and reflect their characters. Note that there is no opening in this series. \
Characters: 8\
I’m going to say this now: Shin Sekai Yori is not an anime about the characters; it is about the story that takes place. The characters were designed to be human, not larger-than-life like Lelouch or Medaka, or eccentric like L or Haruhi. All of the characters, whether human or rat, act like humans: They can be intelligent, they can be irrational, they can be fearful, they can be calm and collected. However, at no point in the series do they become unbelievable. I give this an 8 because the character designs are spot on, and the people involved manage to drive the story forward, but in the world of Kamisu 66, the events that took place could have happened in any village in Japan, not necessarily the one the main character lived in. \
Enjoyment: 10\
I’d like to address something before we move on: This anime is not heavy on fanservice. There was a yaoi/yuri scene that played in very well with the story, given the premise of the show, and many viewers dropped because of this. This only happens once, and is not indicative of the series. It is not like the manga in this respect. \
With that out of the way I’d like to say that Shin Sekai Yori is an immensely enjoyable series. Once the story gets rolling, it shows no signs of stopping. The anime frequently foreshadows future events, yet manages to surprise you every time. The tension in this series is always quite high, and there are quite a few “crowning moments of awesome” in the series. \
Also, this is a series that makes you think. I would recommend watching this anime 3-4 episodes at a time and watch it with friends or go talk about it on forums, simply because the themes involved are quite deep. What is the value of a human life? How far do human rights extend?  There are more, but that would require spoiling the anime. In my humble opinion, this series is probably the most enjoyable of 2012-2013. \
