The story follows a girl named Saki and the rest of her school group, Group One. They uncover that something is definitely rotten in the new world. Viewers beware, this series is not the lighthearted\
          \
        romp that the description and series image portray it to be. It is a post-apocalyptic dystopia with recurring themes of memory, ethics, and morality. Violence, gore, and sexuality populate the series at every turn as the mystery of the Utopia is uncovered. Shinsekai Yori doesn't shy away from depictions of free sexuality, often depicted as 'forced drama' in other series but is merely part of the setting. Unfortunately, the focus on that aspect of society wanes as series goes on, providing one of my few gripes about the plot. Interpersonal relationships make up much of the plot during the first two time arcs but takes a major backseat in the final arc. \
The core of the series is a mystery, and it does it spectacularly. The viewer has a distinct advantage over the characters due to plot devices involving memory and occasional voice-overs by an older Saki. This break allows the viewer to attempt to solve the many mysteries of society. While the major twists will come as no surprise to veterans of the dystopia genre, that by no means diminishes the enjoyment. The first four episodes provide the bulk of the knowledge base for both the viewers and the main characters, which is why those episodes are sometimes criticized for being tedious. It's likely a necessary evil, and is fortunately not provided by a one-and-done plot device. \
One of my favorite things about this series is that there are two antagonists. The first are the Queerats who act as both allies and enemies. The second, more interesting foe is the internal one. The inner conflicts of the characters drive the themes of memory, ethics, and morality in a way that a physical antagonist cannot. The final conflict in the series is very well done, but the quest for victory felt underwhelming and insufficiently explained to me. \
The musical score deserves a special note. Excellent variety of music that added perfectly to the overall tone of the series. Whoever was in charge of that deserves a raise, and then some. Worth listening to just for the music, it is rare to have visual and sound mesh so well. \
