    Note: it’s been quite some time since I actually saw this anime so bear with me with this one, but my feelings towards it have always been quite specific and have never changed so hopefully it’ll work out. This will be done from a mostly critical perspective for once as those are the emotions that stand out the most for me, but please don’t misinterpret this as me hating the show, because that is definitely not the case. Feedback’s always appreciated.\
\
Shinsekai Yori is a show that falls into the category of “misused potential”. It is a series that could, and perhaps should have been one\
          \
        of the best anime in quite some time, but it rather frustratingly stumbles and trips upon itself for completely unnecessary reasons.\
If you take a look at this show from the outside in a general sense, then you’re almost guaranteed to be looking at a masterpiece. The beautiful setting, the original concept along with its darker undertones and the actual sense of realism itself is enough to leave anyone in awe. However if you take a step closer and crack open the shell in order to take a look at the creamy filling of the show, what you’re going to find is sadly not as flawless as first impressions might have made it seem.\
Shinsekai Yori (henceforth abbreviated as SSY) is what I would like to call an ambitious experiment in anime. It is a series that tries to go above and beyond the normal limitations in order to stand out from the crowd. SSY tries to do so much at the same time, and in all honesty succeeds with that fairly well; however it does so at the price of forgetting some of the very basics of what makes an anime great in the first place.\
-- Story – 9/10 --\
Starting with the good parts though, SSY has a rather unique take on how to lead a story onwards. Rather than focusing on its characters directly or even some sort of object or location being the center of attention, SSY’s story is about the world itself. What is this world? How did it end up the way it did, and why? What does the future have in store for it and its inhabitants? How does humanity manage to co-exist with the other intelligent life forms in this world? These are the kind of questions that the story tackles which deviates from the normal a bit, and it does so in a quite interesting and captivating way, as there are a lot of questions to be answered on the grander scale. It also deals with issues such as diplomacy, politics and simply management of a faction in itself.\
From a purely objective standpoint, this is all fine and dandy and all, however it also comes at a price…\
-- Characters – 5/10 --\
…and that is the complete lack of character development. Focusing on the story of the world rather than the story of the characters is interesting and all, but in the end what it did above all was render the main cast of the show into a group of people that would have been better placed as background characters rather than on the front lines.\
Well okay; to revise my initial statement, there *is* character development in this show, a fair bit of it actually, however effectively the entire MC cast of the show is so ridiculously bland and boring from the very start that no matter what kind of dramatic, perilous or supposedly tragic situation they ended up in, I simply couldn’t help but not care about what happened to them. After all, even if someone would end up spontaneously killed along the way, if you don’t even have an opinion about the person in question in the first place, the intended emotional impact just misses its mark. It was most likely that the first thought to come to my mind at such a time would be “good riddance” more than anything.\
-- Art – 7/10 --\
Now this part sends me some quite conflicting signals to be honest. The world of SSY is quite simply beautiful. The vast natural environments and locations which feel like they could have been taken straight out of some MMORPG all have a feeling of reality to them, and it was the kind of setting where you’d like to have a world map available at all times and keep exploring what else it had to offer.\
At the same time however, the actual animations themselves are in all honesty extremely average if you take the fact that this anime came out during the winter of 2012/2013 into account. Above all though, the actual attention to detail regarding the characters’ facial expressions and similar is just simply awkward most of the time, almost as if they were intentionally adding insult to injury for what was already by far the biggest weakness of the show.\
-- Sound – 8/10 --\
SSY uses mainly atmospheric background music for its BGM which fits very well for the theme of the show, and it was a very good OST in general I’d say. There is no one track that stands out though, perhaps with the exception of the ED which was interestingly enough a rehashed version of “Going Home” from Dvořák’s Symphony No. 9.\
The seiyuu cast has some heavy-hitter names in it, which you might argue is a bit sad since their performances had to be wasted on such boring characters, but on the other hand it’d have been even worse without them. Hanazawa Kana stands out from the crowd (as usual you could say) and really tries to bring life to the role she has, but even so a human being can only do so much when you have so little to work with in the first place.\
Regarding the opening theme of the show… it quite simply: Does. Not. Exist.\
Now, I can’t help but ask, was there any reason not to have one? I mean I usually skip the opening of an anime once I’ve heard it once or twice (unless it’s really damn good), but even so was there any actual point of not even having one? Well whatever…\
-- Enjoyment – 8/10 --\
This category is in all honesty really hard to rate and/or comment on. Why? Because SSY does not really feel like an anime to me. Now that can be either a good thing or a bad thing, but the fact of the matter is that it feels more like a documentary mixed together with a historical textbook rather than a show meant for actual entertainment. There are neither any charismatic characters nor any real plot development of the sort that will get your adrenaline running. It is a quite slow story about a utopian world, and spanning a vast timespan while doing so. It gave me the feeling that it was a concept intended to leave you in awe rather than being meant to entertain the viewers, however if it’s not directly entertaining, it won’t leave you in awe in the first place, so it has its own little paradox to work with.\
That being said though, SSY still manages to tease your sense of curiosity concerning what is actually going on behind the scenes of this world, and for that alone I found it pretty interesting so marathoning it over at least not too many sessions wasn’t that bad.\
-- Overall – 8/10 --\
Shinsekai Yori is what I would like to call a blueprint. A theory yet to be perfected about what you can do when you start thinking outside the box. It is a blueprint where all kinds of ideas were added on constantly while its creators were chuckling maniacally to themselves at their own geniuses. However when the invention was all said and done, they suddenly realized that they had forgotten some crucial nuts and bolts in their contraption’s very core; something that was now out of reach and could never be fixed.\
It is a classic case of “what could have been”. SSY leaves me rather annoyed with itself because, while it still in the end was a very good show, it could, and in my opinion, *should* have been so much more. While I don’t think it could ever have reached the top 20 of the MAL rankings as some people seem to claim it should, I’m quite sure it would’ve been top 50 at least if the production hadn’t been so damn sloppy with its very basics.\
That being said though, these kind of experiments need to exist, because humans learn from their mistakes, and maybe next time the 2.0 version of the blueprint will have been patched up and the next true masterpiece will be born.\
All we can do is cross our fingers and hope.\
