    Were I to summarize Shinsekai Yori in a single word, that word would be “intelligent”. If I could add a second word? “Too”.\
Shinsekai Yori is a highly regarded anime about a group of children who live a thousand years in the future. However, their future is not one of advanced technology, of aliens and space-travel. These children – all of the humans we see, really – possess a psychic ability called “Cantus” and live in a society more reminiscent of ancient Japan than anything one might associate with the future. Their village, though seemingly idyllic, is not all that it seems. Outside the holy barrier,\
          \
        fiends, karma demons, and other creatures are said to lurk. Further, the humans are served by the rather disgusting bakenezumi, or queerats, an intelligent species of bi-pedal rats who are, of course, more than they appear.\
This sounds like an interesting premise, and Shinsekai Yori’s first four episodes – often derided as a weak point – hold a great deal of promise. Slow and deliberately paced, they reveal much about the setting and hint at mysteries and incongruities waiting to be revealed. But episode five is where things change. Whilst the first four episodes are slower and feel like a mix of dystopia, fantasy, and horror, the next three feel more like a fast-paced action-adventure. The episodes following those three are more a slow romantic drama, and so on. This isn’t necessarily a weakness, but leads to a rather halting pace early on, as the viewer is confront with jarring shifts in tone. This suggests that, whether or not the writers knew what they wanted to do with this story, they didn’t know how best to achieve it.\
As for the story itself, it only begins to materialize around the halfway point. That’s not to say that the first half of the story is a series of episodic adventures, nor that what occurs there doesn’t have any bearing on what follows, but rather that things take a while to come together. There are several twists and moments of legitimate surprise. All of these things are properly foreshadowed for the astute viewer, and I don’t think the storytelling really relies on twists or surprises to move things along, either. However, due to the shifts in tone mentioned above, the story lacks a certain momentum. There is a bit of deus ex machina near the end, though the characters still need their own ingenuity to resolve the plot. \
The characters prove another chink in Shinsekai Yori’s armor. Our protagonist is a young girl named Saki. She is the narrator. She is the person through whose eyes we witness the story. As protagonists go, Saki is fairly bland. She is competent and courageous and able to face many of the harsh truths that she and her friends uncover as the story unfolds. This last part is a bit of a problem, however. At one point, Saki is told by one of her mentors that her ability to stay calm in the face of the many revelations and events that she encounters means that she will eventually have a position of authority and import within the village. But in a story that is somewhat dystopian in outlook, having a protagonist who is unflappable is a hindrance rather than a strength. These kinds of stories want characters with more vitality. Struggling with unpleasant truths makes a character compelling; however, we never see Saki truly grapple with the injustice and cold utilitarianism of the world in which she lives.\
Saki’s friends prove more capable of emoting than she. (Well, three of them do; Shun is even more of a wet noodle.) However, because the story cleaves so closely to Saki’s perspective, we rarely get a full glimpse of what they’re thinking or how they feel about things. A perfect example of this happens in the middle of the story. Two of Saki’s friends make a decision with significant consequences, but there’s very little foreshadowing that they intend to make this decision. We do discover their reasoning after it happens. On the one hand, this makes their decision surprising; on the other, these characters end up feel like card-board cut-outs for Saki to react to, rather than characters with real emotions or motives. Even a few conversations hinting at certain feelings or thoughts might have alleviated this problem, but to my recollection, no such conversations occur.\
Further, though this story takes place over the course of fourteen years, we never see these characters change. The Saki at the end of the story knows more than the Saki at the beginning, but she’s still largely the same. She’s mature, she’s capable, she’s courageous, she’s kind; she’s all that she was in the beginning, and not much more. Characters are the engine of a story, regardless of its medium. If those characters aren’t compelling in themselves, they should be put in situations that make them compelling. But whilst Saki and her friends can be said to experience a series of events that might be described as interesting, those events fail to make them compelling.\
The most compelling characters are two of the queerats, Squealer and Kiroumaru. Squealer is a character I can’t say that I like, but he manages to be interesting and complex in a way that the human characters are not. Kiroumaru proves a perfect foil and displays as much depth and complexity as Squealer, whilst providing a differing viewpoint on humans, queerats, and their respective societies. Truly, Shinsekai Yori would have benefited from including more of these two.\
A final note about the writing. Prior to watching Shinsekai Yori, I had heard it was a series steeped in moral complexity. This is true to a degree. However, much of that complexity is rather abstract. Whilst events do unfold that are meant to make the viewer ask if the ends ever justify the means, the characters are never asked the same question. This certainly adds a lot to post-viewing discussions, but contributes to the characters seeming shallow and passive. They are never forced to confront the realities of their world in a morally meaningful way.\
Shinsekai Yori’s art direction is a mixed bag. For the most part, the backgrounds are well done, and occasionally they’re even beautiful. Likewise, the overall aesthetic of the series – the architecture, the way the characters dress, the designs of the queerats and wildlife – is one of a kind. I’ve never seen an anime with quite the same look as this one. The animation itself is average, at best. There are some well-animated scenes in the first episode – especially the opening sequence set in modern-day Tokyo – and the unique style of episode ten is befitting of the events that occur in that episode. However, episode five’s animation is abominable, and I noticed during some of the middle episodes that the characters at times seemed a little off, especially when speaking. Shinsekai Yori did not have a large budget, so this is pretty understandable, but it’s worth noting.\
The sound design is better. There are several recurring bits of background music that are affecting and help to enhance the mood of particular scenes. I’m not fluent in Japanese, and so can’t comment on how convincing the voice acting was, but I will say that none of the characters’ voices seemed out of place.\
Often described as deep and profound, Shinsekai Yori is undoubtedly intelligent. It has many ideas, many things to say. This is not a bad thing, in itself, but I think that Shinsekai Yori’s writers were ultimately overwhelmed by all the things they felt they had to say. A shorter series might have forced them to pick a theme and stick to it; a longer one might have allowed them to more adequately explore all the ideas already present in this twenty-five episode anime. As it is, we find ourselves with two central themes and several lesser ideas that are never given enough space to grow. I think, as well, that this emphasis on thought-provoking ideas contributed to several of the problems I tried to touch on in this review.\
There is a lot more that I could say, but I did not want to include any spoilers in this review. I would recommend to prospective viewers that they go in not expecting much from the narrative and characters. Even if you should judge them more favorably than I do, they are still much weaker than the ideas they try to convey. As for myself, I think the goal of fiction, first and foremost, is to tell a good story with engaging characters – ideas and themes and the like being of secondary or even tertiary importance. For writers who want to create intellectually engaging stories, it can be a tricky balancing act between narrative, character, and theme, and for me as a viewer, Shinsekai Yori struck the wrong balance.\
