         Shinsekai Yori (From the New World) gives viewers a glimpse into a perfect society where everyone is gifted with psychic powers. Over the course of the twenty-five episode anime, viewers are treated to the story of five children, and the events that reveal the dark secrets behind their world. \
Story\
     The story that takes place in Shinsekai Yori is what makes this anime so special. Viewers learn about the society and its secrets as the five children’s world is turned upside down. What follows is a beautifully crafted world that challenges the viewer's belief on the\
          \
        morality of a society’s decisions for the greater good. Throughout the three main arcs of Shinsekai Yori, information of the world and brilliant foreshadowing from character’s dialogue is presented all leading up to the final arc that combines it all for the amazing conclusion. After finishing the anime, I had the urge to just sit down and discuss with somebody about the choices of the characters, and the grey morality of the entire show. \
Characters  \
     During the course of Shinsekai Yori, the viewer is shown the lives of five children who are all sorted into the same group for their school at the beginning of the show. Viewers watch as these children grow throughout the show, and are able to see how their ideas and beliefs change. The show focuses on the character of Saki Watananabe, and how the effects of one summer trip completely changes the view of the world her and her friends share. Watching these children grow into adulthood forms an attachment to the characters, and caused me to care about them when the danger ramps up later on into the story. By using Saki as the eyes of the viewer, we are able to learn about the world as she does, and by using different points in their lives we are able to see how the characters react to the rules of the society around them. \
Sound   \
     The soundtrack for Shinsekai Yori is perfect for the world that exist in this show. Tracks like Going Home and Traditional Song of Shadows are perfect for the feudal Japanese village setting, and can give the feeling of dread in intense moments. Most of the voice work is well done, and each character’s voice seems to fit their design.\
Art \
     The art design in Shinsekai Yori does its job of creating the village and its inhabints of Saki Watananabe’s world. The design of the village shows how the citizens don’t rely on technology anymore and live in a pre-technology Japan. The creature design does a great job of showing the new otherworldly monsters that inhabit the world, and the design of the Queerrats being my personal favorite. Each of the main character designs fit for their personalities, and makes a logical progression on how that character would look with each of the anime’s arcs. \
Overall    \
     In conclusion, Shinsekai Yori is an anime that will stick with me for a long time. The beautifully crafted world and its society built around psychic powers was extremely interesting world building for me. Watching five children grow up in this world while learning about how it came to be, and the morally ambiguous ways that the society protected this world provided an engaging story, and provided thought provoking questions such as “Does the ends justify the means” and “When does something count as being equal to a human?” The show ends on an extremely satisfying conclusion, and makes the viewer feel like all the knowledge they learned of this world pays off in the end.     \
