    Shinsekai Yori presents us with interesting world building (as well as an interesting world in itself), a good plot, a great soundtrack and beautiful visuals. It also presents some interesting questions of morality, and even though most of those questions have already been asked in other series, it manages to present them in such a way that didn’t make them feel redundant. However, the show’s major downfall were its characters, 90% of whom were just flat out terribly written. Nonetheless, this is still one of the best anime to have come out in recent years and deserves to be watched by anyone, unless they refuse\
          \
        to watch anything even slightly challenging to the brain.\
\
PLOT/WORLD\
Both the plot and the world of Shinsekai Yori are nothing short of brilliant. The plot is set up in different arcs, with each arc moving forward the main mystery of this world and effectively building upon itself. The show keeps you guessing throughout the very end, but also presents you with enough information that you CAN keep guessing without it feeling desperate.\
Despite a pretty large amount unanswered questions and abandoned plot threads, the plot was solid. The main plot of the show is largely unpredictable, mainly because the show is really good at giving out information at the exact moment that its needed, but not a second earlier. Even though I did manage to predict one or two elements of the conclusion at the start of the show, it did manage to keep me guessing throughout the majority, which is more than I can say for other anime. The arcs in which the show was divided, however, were extremely predictable but I wasn’t too bothered by this.\
The arcs themselves varied greatly in terms of quality. Overal, they were really good. Personally, I believe the second arc (right after the introduction arc) to be the weakest. It actually put me off the series for a while. Others seemed to dislike the introduction arc the worst, which is completely understandable because it is, in comparison to the rest of the shows, very slow moving. I personally liked them, though, for their feeling of atmosphere. \
The atmosphere is probably the best thing of this entire show, as it really makes the world. It gives this universe a sense of realism, even if what they are showing to you is completely unrealistic. At the same time, though, it supplies you with just enough magical wonder that you can keep being amazed at what they are portraying. It also keeps the air of mystery high, even when there is nothing going on. \
The world, even without the atmosphere, is also very intriguing. I love the idea behind it and, without giving too much spoilers, I really like how they portrayed the leaders. Not as tyrannical bastards, as we often do in the here in the West, but as people who have done both good and bad things and have made mistakes just like us. I really appreciate this.\
Apart from the early episodes being a bit slow, the only other problem I can see people having with the plot are the time skips. The time skips really hurt the pacing of this show, as for a large amount of time, nothing happens, then suddenly, we are years later and a lot has happened off screen. But overall, I think that they were justified and not used as badly as in some other anime I’ve seen. A lot of the things that happened within the show couldn’t have happened without the characters growing older, and without the time skips, it would have had to show all the time passing. This, most likely, would have hurt the pacing even more. So, even though I do believe that they could have been handled better, I don’t mind the time skips too much.\
I’m not going to go into the questions of morality I’ve mentioned in the introduction too much, because that would mean major spoilers. I do have to say that gray morality is handled in this anime quite well, though if I really nitpick I could probably point out where they could have done it better. They also present much more philosophical questions than just ‘gray morality’, like: “What does it mean to be human?”. I found these questions to be presented in quite an intriguing way, and even though they have been asked a million times before, I never felt like they were beating a dead horse.\
All in all, both the plot and the world are solid, with the world building being one of the best I’ve seen thus far in anime.\
\
SOUND/ANIMATION\
The animations is fluid, with the backgrounds being especially beautiful. I’m not too fond of the character designs with the long limbs, but they managed to work with them quite nicely. The animation on the first ending song especially was brilliant. I also really liked the art style they used there. \
Interesting to note is that Shinsekai Yori has no openings, instead preferring to dive right into the story. I believe that this is probably the best decision they could have made, as it really adds to the feel of the episode. I’m fond of neither of the ending themes, though I do like the second one a bit better than the first. \
The background music, however, is a different story. On its own, the soundtrack isn’t that great, but coupled with the visuals, it’s amazing. It really manages to set the mood and tone to the story, as well as add a lot to the previously mentioned brilliant atmosphere. I’m really grateful for this. \
\
CHARACTERS\
Saving the worst for the last: this is where the show almost falls apart. Despite all the praise I’ve given it so far, I really cannot do anything but critique this part of the show: the characters. \
Our main character, Saki, suffers from the worst flaw that any character can have: inconsistency. \
Having an inconsistent character is the worst flaw that any story can have. Even writing a Mary Sue as your main lead is better than writing an inconsistent lead. Because when your character is inconsistent, it becomes impossible to feel for them. \
Inconsistency can stem from a lot of things, but the main one (and also the source of problem here) is excessive plot armor. Plot armor, for those who don’t know, is when a character becomes invincible purely because the plot demands it. Almost all main characters have some degree of plot armor, and this can be forgiven. After all, if your MC dies, your story is over. You need them to at least survive until the climax, and therefore, you use plot armor. \
However, you do need to work within the limits that you, as the writer, have set for your character. If your character can’t fly, you don’t make them fly because it’s the only way for them to escape your villain. If your character is loyal, you don’t make them abandon their friends the moment it becomes convenient. It’s that simple. \
Shinsekai Yori does not seem to get this simple rule. Saki is so continuously inconsistent that I honestly have no idea what her character is supposed to be. Sometimes, she is a great leader, other times, she can get no one to listen to her. Sometimes, her cantus is above average strong, other times, she can’t even get something to move the right way. Sometimes, she is smart, other times, she can’t even think up a sentence that makes sense. Sometimes, she stands for her believes, other times, she mindlessly goes along with what the others want. Sometimes, she has a strong mental stability, other times, she breaks down at nothing. The only thing even semi-consistent about her character is her infatuation with Shun, which is just pitiful.\
The only clue I have to what her character was supposed to be is what the other characters say about her. According to them, she is supposed to be smart, strong, a good leader, with a cantus that is not above average. However, I have seen her do things that directly oppose all of these traits multiple times in the anime. I have also seen her exhibiting all of these traits, but only when it suited the plot.\
Switching personality is fine if it is done in a linear way: Person A was nice at the start of the show, but when Person B died, they became very cold towards Person C, because they wanted to distance themselves. This is fine, because it shows character development. However, Saki switches back and forth with no rhyme or reason to it, basically doing whatever the story demands. \
For a character like this, that basically does whatever the plot tells her to do, development is impossible. Because she has no set character, she is exactly the same as she was at the end as the beginning of the show: nothing and everything. Sure, she is seems different than she seemed in the first episode, but I can’t tell if that is because she has truly changed, or because the plot knew that she had to look different. For all I know, she could switch back at the drop of a hat. \
When a character doesn’t develop and has no set personality, they become impossible to care for. Because of the insane amounts of plot armor, she is virtually the only character untouchable and the audience knows it. Therefore, we never feel scared when she’s in danger. In fact, if she was killed, I doubt that anyone would care beyond being shocked that they actually killed of their main character. \
In short, Saki is the worst kind of character imaginable and it really, really hurts not only the show, but also the other characters.\
The main victim of Saki’s inconsistency is Satoru, one of the other main characters. He is with Saki the most, and therefore, is the biggest victim of her failure as a character. Even though his own personality is set, it can change at random depending on whether the plot wants him to oppose Saki or not. This becomes really annoying after a while, as it feels like they are forcing him to bend in ways he never should have. Still, he is probably the best out of the main five, because he does get development, even if it is somewhat inconsistent and sporadic. \
Shun is the Gary Stu of the anime. He is perfect, or at least, that’s what they want us to believe. In reality, however, he is an asshole. Honestly, I started off liking him, but I came to hate him for being a complete jerk to everyone who isn’t Saki; and then I mean Satoru in particular. If you don’t care about spoilers for character relationships (I assume that no one does unless you’re watching a harem): Satoru totally has a very strong crush on Shun (if not something more; I would argue that his feelings are almost as strong as Safu’s), and Shun enters a relationship with him, despite not having feelings for Satoru at all. This is a dick move for a number of reasons, not in the least because you don’t toy with someone like that. Honestly, what the hell was he thinking? If you don’t like someone, don’t enter a relationship with them. Done. It makes you look like an asshole.\
This actually leads me into my next subject: the romantic subplots. Yes, there is both shounen-ai and shoujo-ai in this. Deal with it. Honestly, it’s only one episode. I have no idea why everyone is making a big deal out of that. I like none of the romantic subplots: not the straight, not the queer, none of them. They all annoy me to no end, but like I said, they are not too prominent and sort of justified by the world they live in, so I’m going to let it slide.\
In short the characters... Oh, sorry, did I forget to talk about the other two from the main five, Maria and Mamoru? Well, the show did too. Maria has slightly more character than Mamoru, but that is nothing to be proud of, considering that Mamoru could’ve easily been a side character instead of a main one. Neither of them get development, and I care for neither of them. They, like the rest of the characters, are mere pawns for the plot.\
The problem with Shinsekai Yori is that the characters don’t drive the plot, the plot drives the characters. This results in an inconsistent main character, and other characters that can range from unlikable to bland. The only exception I’m willing to give is Squeler, who was actually pretty interesting, but again, only because the plot demanded him to be. \
So yeah. The characters are terrible. Sorry for the rant I went on there, but they just grate me to no end.\
\
CONCLUSION\
Even though the characters are absolutely hideous, the show still holds up pretty good, getting a seven even after I subracted two points purely for them. Everything but them ranges from good to brilliant. Even if the plot does have some minor flaws, they are forgivable in the end. The animation is great and the music really adds to the atmosphere of the show. The world and its atmosphere are both brilliant, and totally make this anime worth watching for them alone. I say go watch it and ignore the characters, because the show really deserves to be watched.",
