    This is my first review so I apologize if it's not up to par or runs on for too long! In addition to the anime review, I'll also be comparing the anime to the original novel.\
I was (kinda) introduced to Shinsekaiyori by my sister and the plot sounded interesting, so I decided to give the original novel a try. And I'm really glad I did, because it ended up being one of my favorite novels of all time. So naturally, I decided to give the anime a try as well, and I was not disappointed.\
The thing that impressed me the most was how loyal the\
          \
        anime was to the original novel. The anime follows the novel exactly for the most part without cutting any important scenes or characters, and also without adding any unnecessary fillers. There was only one big scene involving two of the main characters that was cut (or rather heavily abbreviated) in the anime but this did not interfere with the flow of the story in the least. The pacing of the episodes was well done and the end of each always left you eager to find out what happens next. I was also pleased with the flashbacks at the beginning of some of the early episodes showing what happened over the course of 1000 years before the story begins. \
The art is fantastic. Most of the characters and creatures appeared and sounded as I would've imagined from reading the novel. It was also a plus that some of my favorite seiyuus (Taniyama Kishou, Kaji Yuuki, Hanazawa Kana of course) were used! I guess at first I imagined the Bakenezumis to be a little \"cuter\" but I felt their design in the anime gave them more of an impact (especially Kiroumaru since I wasn't imagining him to be so tall) The scenery shots, especially the sunset shots, are breathtaking. The next time you hear Dvořák's 9th symphony, the setting sun of Kamisu 66-chou is guaranteed to come to mind.\
One factor that makes the story so great is how much it makes you think. Even though the story is obviously fiction, it does not eliminate the possibility that a similar scenario could happen in real life in the future. It makes you contemplate what measures a government might take in order to create the perfect society or \"utopia\". It makes you consider your sexuality, whether we as humans are truly no different from bonobos when we copulate for pleasure or to reduce stress. There are many philosophical themes hidden throughout the story that will keep your mind working as you learn about the dark, blood-stained history of the Shinsekaiyori world.\
The story is also filled with a large number and variety of characters, both human and non-human. Each character has their own unique personality and significant role to the overlying plot. However, you may be disappointed if you become attached to a specific character as the author has no problem killing off characters, even if they only get one episode of screen time, but this only adds to the story's suspense. As the story progresses, we watch the characters as they grow, change, and gradually move down the paths that society has laid out for them. \
Shinsekaiyori is one of the best stories I've ever read, and in turn one of the best anime I've ever watched. The art is fantastic, the voices and character designs are spot-on, and the story is so well written and thought out. Props to both the author Kishi Yuusuke and director Ishihama Masashi for bringing this brilliant work to life. A definite recommendation to any fans of the dystopian genre.\
P.S. Although I don't hate her, I do find the main character Saki to be quite annoying overall, and I think Taneda Risa did an astounding job in ensuring her annoyance in the anime as well.\
