          \
        similar; implying that thoughts are powerful. Thankfully, this does not turn out into a mushy experience. Shinsekai Yori is the story of a young girl named Saki Watanabe who grows up in a village in Japan. The story itself is presented as a reminiscence of a much older Saki as she recounts the events that unfolded as she grew up. The central plot tool here is the effects of 'Cantus', a psychic power present in all humans in the anime, and the chaos it causes despite being tightly reined in by the community. \
Very honestly put, the story is rather wayward. The central and final conflict happens to be about a species called 'queerats' trying to gain their independence from the humans. Strangely, this is something that is almost entirely left out until the last few episodes. On the other hand the story builds up a rather interesting and gripping piece about fiends and demons (humans who have lost control of their Cantus), and Cantus leakage, over the earlier episodes only to seemingly abandon the entire idea by the time the anime is half way through. It was rather grating to see things gain and lose relevancy throughout the anime. While the idea itself is novel, the fact that it was implemented badly made it look like the Shinsekais drawing the Yoris were rather halfhearted about things.\
This doesn't mean that the story is a let down. Quite to the contrary, viewers will be pleased to note that their butts are still on the seats and eyes still on the screen by the time they reach the end of episode 25. The plot(s) (plural; since it is more meaningful to consider the 'queerat' story independent of the 'Cantus' story) are well thought-out, properly paced and most of all, satisfyingly explained. As satisfyingly explained as possible in a fantasy setup that is. Thankfully, both plot lines also manage to transition seamlessly, so most people will acquire the inevitable feeling of discontent only after finishing the anime and updating their anime lists.\
The animation is something that needs to be mentioned. While it was top notch, in some places, it felt as if the cell shading (yes, nobody shades cells anymore) somehow changed hands. This was most visible in one of the earlier episodes, where the tone of the visuals changed rather noticeably. Probably budget cuts.\
Coming over to the audio and aural experience, it can be said that everything was excellent. The voice acting cast (Japanese) was spot-on and were also cast well. Hiroaki Hirata, as the queerat commander Kiromaru, deserves a special mention. Among all the characters/voice cast combinations in the anime, his was the best and suited the character to a T. The music, OP/ED and background score is a mix of things ranging from indomitable (and beautiful) Kana Hanazawa to Antonín Dvořák. There is never a dull moment in the anime thanks to all the sounds being in all the right places throughout the 25 episodes. However, a stern look could be given to the lip-synchronization.\
The characters in the anime are well done too. The anime follows the usual precedent for its genre by killing a character or two every few episodes and letting the MC cry a bit. This, of course, happens to be the protagonist's strength too. In fact, the 'strength' of the protagonist is explicitly mentioned several times but nobody will ever be certain about what it is. Top contenders include the ability to lose friends, crying and 'strength' itself.\
The biggest pitfall for Shinsekai Yori is its characters' tendency to yammer away at the most inopportune of moments. Being chased by monsters? Hey Shun, let's stop and talk a bit. Is our friend missing? I want to talk about my feelings for a moment now. Sometimes, the anime feels like Skyrim with all its lengthy dialogue in all the wrong places. It makes sense if a character is introspecting in the midst of a crisis (hello Naruto): this can be explained as time being irrelevant when presenting thoughts; but it makes absolutely no sense to see characters talking about friends when they're an inch away from death. Another thing that needs to be mentioned are the facial expressions and emotions which were mistimed in many instances. An example: Kiromaru, Saki and Satoru Asahina plan an attack in the final episode and Kiromaru leaves to execute the first part of the plan. What are Saki and Satoru up to? It is a life-or-death situation and they are both sitting down on a slab and calmly discussing things. One would expect the pacing here to be much faster with both of them getting their environment and themselves ready for their part of the plan, but no, they take this wonderful opportunity to relax and share a few feels.\
All that said, Shinsekai Yori is definitely an anime that's worth watching. It's a well-rounded meal that'll leave one feeling satisfied but missing that one small, inexplicable bit. A setup for a sequel perhaps? Only time will tell.\
