    Shinsekai Yori was one of the more polarizing series of the Fall 2012 season.  Its dark themes, twisting and complex story, and slow pace turned a lot of viewers off.  But for those that saw it through to the end, they were treated to what I consider to be the best show of the year.\
Story:\
Shinsekai Yori's story is set in a post-apocalyptic world, but in something of an inversion of genre expectations, we're introduced to a pastoral Japan, that's seemingly peaceful and well-maintained.  Of course, we know things are not quite what they seem.  How is a society of telekinetic humans\
          \
        able to thrive given the very nature of such a power, and its role in the collapse of ancient (our) civilization?  The rabbit hole goes deep, and the unraveling of this mystery through the eyes of Saki and the children of Group 1 is the engine that keeps this story moving.  It's an engaging, often unsettling, and always though-provoking tale.\
Characters: 9/10\
We're being told the story of Shinsekai Yori through the yes of Saki Watanabe, who starts the series as a 12 year, freshly awakened to her telekinetic powers.  The story spans a considerable amount of time, and throughout it, we learn about the world, and experience Saki's growth into one of the strongest female characters in recent anime.  The supporting cast isn't as well fleshed out as Saki, but they are almost always believable, and some standouts, like Shun, Maria, Satoru, and Tomiko can carry the show on their own for stretches.  The unreliable memories and perspectives of Saki and her classmates is part of what makes experiencing this story so compelling.\
Art: 7/10\
The character design, backgrounds, and color palette of Shinsekai Yori are excellent.  Unfortunately, the same can not be said about the animation itself.  This is a sometimes slow, dialogue heavy show, but there are a number of action heavy sequences throughout, and the animation quality can drop noticeably.  During fights, and other high action, the visuals often can't keep pace with the intensity of the events that are unfolding.   Episodes 5 and 10 have a different director and art style altogether, and while I appreciate the impulse to try something potentially interesting, it just doesn't work here.\
Sound: 9/10\
The voice acting is consistently excellent, and the use of music (especially Dvorak's \"From the New World\") throughout the series amplifies the emotional impact of the experience.\
Enjoyment: 10/10\
Watching Shinsekai Yori takes work.  The plot takes a while to develop, but you'll be rewarded for sticking with it.  There is a deep mystery to this world, and facts are hard to come by.  The plot is delivered in such a way that revelations often come by way of inference.  The fate of some characters, and the resolution of certain issues aren't bypassed - these aren't plot holes - but you won't always be told exactly how things happened.  Just like the main characters, you'll often be left to sort through incomplete information as you try to figure out what has actually transpired.  So, how enjoyable is Shinsekai Yori?  If you're like me, you'll find it to be an absolute blast.\
Overall: 9/10\
Taking this story on was ambitious, and there were some notable stumbles.  The animation is sometimes sloppy and rushed,  and in its worst moments, it can be utterly jarring.  Additionally, the pacing and editing is often inconsistent - it's sometimes brilliant (episode 16), and sometimes dismal (episode 5).\
Those issues aside, the outstanding plot, world creation, and characters are what set Shinsekai Yori apart.  The world of Shinsekai Yori, and the mystery that surrounds it, is excellently crafted.  We experience the world through the eyes of Saki.  We're never privy to more than what Saki, knows and experiences.  We know, as well as Saki does, that things are not as they seem, but like her, you won't be handed anything.  Sifting between reality and illusion is as important for the audience, as it is for the main cast.  This is the kind of show that demands engagement in order to be fully enjoyed.  If you can handle the animation hiccups, and have patience, you'll be rewarded with a unique, challenging, and beautiful piece of science-fiction.",
