                          \
    It starts out as the seemingly typical dystopian story, where horrible events prior result in a complete reworking of the social order. As per usual, the narrator hints at a hidden menace festering within this newly established society, and the audience automatically expects an impending change. But while it does go the way of similar stories in that the status quo is revealed to be warped at best and sinister at worst, the story and narration possess several elements that elevate Shinsekai Yori.\
Story-wise, it does not merely utilize the evil society versus select group of special individuals trope. It’s not as simplistic as that. It\
          \
        shows that even in a social group there exist factions with different, sometimes competing, ideals and objectives. And often the same thing can mean different things to different people, creating conflict and imbalance. The characters have different ideas about progress and what it takes to sustain that progress. They have different ideas about freedom, justice, and equality. \
This approach does the story good as it precludes the unnecessary, overly dramatic vilification of the characters. Here, you don’t have straight up, uncomplicated good and evil. You have people who are weak, terrified, angry, desperate, hopeful, determined, protective, bigoted, maniacal. And all these varying wants and emotions create the tensions in the story. \
There isn’t just one side against the other. It’s about a multilayered society the interpretation of which depends on the context you choose to view it in, depends on the character whose eyes you choose to look through. Shinsekai Yori does a good job of exploring the psyche of the individuals who occupy the different aspects of this new world while simultaneously establishing the part they play in the grand scheme of things, the consequences and resulting realities of their actions and decisions. \
The narrative style lends further strength. By making effective use of subtlety and contrast, it creates a story that feels progressively anxious and foreboding. First through the choice of narration, then through the contrast between the past and present societies, and last through the actions of the characters versus the reaction of the viewer. \
Instead of adopting a third-party POV, the viewer is immediately thrust into one of the main character’s perspective of events. The story’s main timeline is from when the narrator was much younger, so the narrator adopts a tone that is older and seemingly wiser, a direct contrast to naivety and innocence of the events she is relating and the people she and her friends used to be. This treats the viewers to the dual sensations of an adult’s misgivings and the insistence and folly of youth. And because the narrator implies that the misgivings are valid, the tension is even more taut, as the viewers are unable to do anything but go along for the ride, all the while knowing that something terrible will indeed be happening.   \
There is also the contrast between the urban, technologically-advanced past society and the rural backdrop of the present society. It is later shown how this conscious decision to forgo technology and commercial progress poses certain disadvantages.\
Another contrast also exists between how casually the characters react to and experience violence, and the violence itself and the viewers’ perception of it. There is a marked disconnect between the two. The characters see nothing wrong with it, they treat it us a matter of fact, while the viewer is forced to simultaneously react to the violence and recalibrate his or her moral compass to adapt to the characters’ world normalized bloodshed and slavery.  \
Everything makes for an ominous, nail-biting journey disguised beneath a misleadingly subdued narrative. The tension and horror isn’t brought to the viewer via extreme gore and violence, as is typical of many “dark” anime nowadays. In Shinsekai Yori, said tension and horror build as the viewer understands more about the world and the characters. It is a horror that stains and lingers far more effectively because it wasn’t arbitrarily imposed, it was planted and coaxed inside the viewers, and grew with the story and their understanding of it.  \
I can’t recommend this anime enough. \
