                          \
    Shinsekai Yori is an award-winning novel which was adapted as a twenty five-episode anime by A-1 Pictures from 2012 to 2013. Despite being hailed by numerous anime critics, it was commercially unsuccessful.  Honestly speaking, I am one of those who wondered why it failed to garner financial success because this is one of the most ambitious and the strongest titles I have watched from an anime series in 2013.\
While a dystopian world as a theme is nothing new to the world of anime, the source material's way of handling it stands out among others of its kind.  Topics like genocide, inhumane scientific experiments,\
          \
        racism and moral ambiguity are prevalent in the series while being hidden under a very calm surface. Hence, the false sense of peace the Shinsekai Yori has in its first half really gave a misplaced superiority complex among its populace and an uncomfortable feeling to the viewer. The pressure in keeping the status quo built up until it was destroyed in full swing when the suppressed struck back. While certainly horrific, this manner of storytelling also left an indelible mark to the minds of the viewer. It involved teenage characters at some time but the series is not for the young.\
Shinsekai Yori also featured one of the best presentation of moral ambiguity in recent anime history. The importance of status quo, the inequality between two different races and the cat and mouse chase (only to be overturned later on) were presented in an impeccable manner. Both sides have their point, no one is exactly right and people can sometimes be more monstrous than a real one. \
One legitimate flaw of Shinsekai Yori’s setup is it took too long before anything major happened. The first fourteen episodes’ plot progression was too slow to the extent of many dropping the show midway. However, these were carefully spent on world-building for the viewers to really immerse themselves in the series. Hence, when the action began, it went full force which left many viewers in awe and those who dropped it earlier to watch it again and be entranced by its beauty. Another legit flaw is the show has a habit of throwing jargons like cacti, minoshiro and queerats as if the viewer has knowledge about those beforehand. Fortunately, these are also explained in a thoughtful manner later on.\
While I also love Shinsekai Yori so much that it borders on fanboyism, the artwork is its biggest weakness. Due to its experimental premise that does not sound commercial at all, it seemed like it suffered several budget cuts in its run. The quality of the artwork violently changed several times throughout the series. The colors used ranged from really good hues to dull and the character designs were drawn inconsistently at times. It is kind of jarring and it might turn off viewers that are critical with the visual appeal of an anime. More so, the camera focus is distracting at times. A casual audience would not want to spend minutes staring at Saki’s crotch while she speaks.\
Fortunately, Shinsekai Yori compensated its lack of visual appeal with its very beautiful and haunting sound which complemented the whole series. It knows when to use strings during climactic moments, the percussions to accent the cat and mouse chase between humans and queerats and silence is amply given to emphasize scenes where the characters are in deep-thinking mode.\
One notable aspect of Shinsekai Yori is it lacks an opening song for a good reason. The \"Traditional Song of Shadows\" is one of the most epic background music I have heard from an anime which fits just right with its very ambitious nature. The piece \"Going Home\" was also used numerous times in the series and was interpreted to be used after the havoc to a haunting effect. The ending song, while an upbeat one, foreshadowed Saki’s very long journey towards attaining a truly peaceful life.\
Every character in Shinsekai Yori is well explored, from their motives to their ultimate fate. The series was able to make them very compelling to the extent that you might even find it hard to side with the main characters because the reasons of the antagonist were well explained and the humans were not exactly perfect either.\
Watanabe Saki is also one of the best anime characters that I have seen in my entire anime watching experience. She is not too smart, she is an average looking girl and she is relegated to the role of an observer many times in the series. Yet what makes her human is her unstoppable will to change the world despite is negativities and her ability to go on without further sacrificing what's important with her. While she did not forgive what was wrongly done, she shows mercy when the perpetrator has suffered enough for his sin. \
Squealer, on the other hand, is one of the most fleshed antagonist in anime. His journey, from a mere queerat to humanity’s vessel of destruction was shown amply. His reasons for doing so is also sufficiently given to the viewer. His speech at the end of the series made the last episode as one of the best endings in any anime ever. \
In the end, Shinsekai Yori is truly a one of a kind experience and is deserved to be called one of the defining animes of 2013. If you want a thought provoking show which intricately built its characters and its world, this one is for you.\
