                          \
    Shinsekai Yori inhabits an odd place when it comes to anime. Its a deeply psychological themed anime that explores the viewers unease as the plot develops while at the same time it feels like an odyssey as you watch the five young children that are at the center of the narrative grow up from the beginning of the show until its end. Set in a post-dystopian world, the world of Shinsekai Yori is ordered and beautiful - but in order to achieve order, peace, and stability the world is built on what some may call immoral and dirty societal practices that are deemed necessary to\
          \
        keep society functioning.\
In many ways Shinsekai Yori is more in line with western stories like The Giver or the Hunger Games than it is with anything in Anime. Partly because of this a viewer may come into this show not realizing what they are getting into. This show will make you feel uncomfortable or think, if you are willing to allow yourself to be uncomfortable and think. Unlike other dystopian stories, as viewers we get to see the proverbial making of the sausage and see exactly how/why the society functions as it does and as viewers we can come to appreciate how this society ended up emerging the way it does. For everything it does, Shinsekai Yori also tries to remain rooted in realistic and logical steps and any of the supernatural powers/effects feel like they naturally flow from an incredibly well built world. \
Warnings:\
As mentioned above, this show does feel more western in some ways than many anime. Other warnings, this is not a Shonen or a Seinen and while there is some action, the action is meant as a means of exploring the world and the complex societal relationships within the story. There were some gay/lesbian scenes in this anime, however they are not gratuitous and have a legitimate place in the anime as part of the worldbuilding necessary to setup the society these children live in. Some viewers and reviews have docked this anime for the display of these scenes simply because of the existence of said gay/lesbian scenes without acknowledging the fact it was a brief (and fairly subtle) part of the world building. Finally, this story explores several threads of this society and does not simply just explore one aspect of this dystopian society. For those who struggle with a narrative that explores multiple aspects and themes, this may not be the anime for you.\
Art:\
The tones and colors are quite stark and contribute to the exploration of the fears and hopes of these children as they grow up in this society. Shinsekai Yori had several guest directors who directed their episodes in different art styles compared to the main narrative and while this can be jarring for some, it largely feels like it adds to the world. Animation is largely fluid and seamless, however some lower budget episodes are somewhat apparent.\
Sound:\
As far as OSTs go this is a haunting OST. In fact I would say almost traumatizingly haunting. Fear, hope, and unease all help create the feeling that this is really coming from a \"Brave new world\". If I had to compare this OST to another OST that fit beautifully alongside the world it had built, it would be Spice and Wolf. Strangely this anime does not have an OP, however it does have an amazing ED that feels like it continues the exploration of your emotions.\
Characters:\
There is something satisfying watching characters grow up from immature selves to their more mature adult selves over the course of a show like this. None of the characters are over the top and you will likely not place them in a top 10 list of your most memorable characters, however each character feels like they genuinely fit the world they were placed in. There is such a thing as quiet strength in people - a quiet strength in people who have to overcome adversity and the main characters in this show definitely have that strength. Which once again brings me back to the point that in some ways this feels more like something Western than Japanese at times.\
Enjoyment:\
This one is a bit of a strange category. I can say I enjoyed thinking about this world, watching the changes and natural human inconsistencies rub up against each other and cause the conflicts that kept the plot of this anime going. It felt natural, logical, creative, innovative, and in many ways awe-inspiring. The usage of Dvorak's New World symphony in this anime added to the feeling of this feeling like an epic. However, this anime does leave feelings of unease and while I can say 100% that I enjoyed this anime its something that you have to ruminate on and can't exactly jump into a rewatch immediately after viewing it for the first time.\
Overall I would give this anime a 10/10. While there are some arguably minor flaws like in some inconsistencies in art direction, the ideas and themes it explores are both beautiful and leave enough room for the viewer to make his/her own judgments without being spoon fed \"right\" or \"wrong\" views. This anime assumes you are wise enough to judge the world around you and then ultimately realize a harsh truth, all we know is that we know nothing. Dissertations could be made on this anime and it definitely does deserve rewatching to pick up on themes that one may have missed the first time or to think about certain aspects if they were taken to their logical conclusion. In many ways I would call this a masterpiece, but I would also call it something sort of strange or alien in the world of anime as there isn't really anything like it.\
