The first problem that bothered me with SSY is that none of the parts seem to compliment each other properly, despite appearances. They do not so much each add to Saki's life experience as seem to be a mishmash of different storylines that should converge to a deep overarching narrative, but seldom manage to.\
In a clear (non-spoily) metaphor: let's say I wanna make a cake. I'm getting my ingredients, I read the recipe, I smash and mix and stir and put in the oven. Then I eat it and it's good.\
