    This is probably the most unique, non-formulaic anime I've ever seen, and because of that I was willing to overlook some major issues with pacing, characters, and plotline, etc. Shinsekai Yori is weird in that it takes place in the future, but does not involve giant robots or space travel. There is \"magic\" in the form of psychokinetic ability, although there is a pretty decent scientific explanation behind it and many of the quirky aspects of the setting. This show would be very hard to place in any of the traditional genres/categories because of this, although if anything I would call Shinsekai Yori more of\
          \
        a dark fantasy than anything else.\
 I also liked that the story was told through the perspective of children, which allowed the viewer to come to understand the world of Shinsekai Yori in a more naturally progressive way. I gave the series and overall rating of 8 because of the aforementioned flaws, but it's a series that is so remarkably unique that I would recommend it to anyone who can handle its very dark themes.\
*Spoilers\
The main problem with the show, at least in my book, was the timing/progression of the story. The time skips, particularly the big one that started in episode 8, left me trying to figure out what was going on for a number of episode while also trying to process new information that was coming in. While I understand that the creators wanted the viewers to be just as disoriented as the remaining children as group 1, I believe they could have handled this a bit more elegantly. the way that it was handled made it feel like I'd accidentally skipped episodes. The fact that they combined this with memory fragmentation was what made it particularly problematic.\
The awkward progression of the story also led to a general feeling that some parts of the story went by too quickly/slowly, and many scenes felt as if they could've been replaced by something better.  The arc with the search for for Mamoru and then Maria/Mamoru for example, seemed to take a very long time even though we know how important that action was for the main plotline. The boulder game tournament from one of the early episodes, also, felt a bit unnecessary. There were far more fascinating things going on, why spend an entire episode on that? \
That brings me to the characters. I can't say that any of them really stuck out to me. Maybe this was the point, but the queerats - squealer and kiromaru - were the particularly interesting ones in the second half of the show. Although their motivations were obvious, their unpredictability actually made them scary. The main characters, by comparison, were predictable and I didn't find the various romantic entanglements between them all that convincing for whatever reason.\
Although the execution wasn't great, the story of Shinsekai Yori was what really elevated the show from the 6-7 \"averagish\" range in my book. It was interesting that some of the most important moments of the story were left up to the imagination. For example the writers knew that leaving the details of Maria/Mamoru's fate outside of the scope of the story made it all the more crushing upon the reveal. And then you begin to understand the feelings of apprehension whenever squealer appeared -- that was a brilliant design by the creators.\
So in the end, Ignoring a few plotholes, and random unbelievably stupid decisions (i.e. wasting the psycho buster), the show as a whole told a really fascinating story that ended in a very strange/unique feeling of emptiness. I don't think the show should be ranked along with the very elite of anime, but it should be watched if you can handle this kind of show. \
