The premise of a totalitarian regime (with literal hypnosis, assassinations and quasi slavery) is too universally disliked for a show that tries to ask a morally grey question. Hearing everyone say \"Squealer did nothing wrong!\", I expected the statement to be ironic, but it turns out that it's entirely true.\
I will now try to summarize the big question this show throws at you, you be the judge: \"Is it morally okay to enslave an equally intelligent species as long as you're more powerful than them?\"\
The twist at the end also does not change anything about this question, if anything, it makes it even easier to answer.\
Art:\
I generally really liked the down to earth visuals as well as the entire setting. My only big problems with the art is that, due to how androgynous most younger characters seem to be, a lot of the characters had a very blatant same-face issue. This was especially obvious due to the amount of close-ups we got.\
Some kudos also for trying a more artsy approach for some scenes, but I think they often fell just a bit short, without real symbolism to properly warrant them.\
Sound:\
The sound really didn't stick out to me that much. They did a really good job of creating an atmosphere for certain scenes, but this also came over as lazy sometimes, to cover up for the poor character writing and script.\
Special mention to both endings, which are very lovely songs.\
Characters:\
This is the big one.\
The characters range from 'Tolerable but lazy' to 'This dude(tte) is literally just a plot device with a face'.\
Saki, the main protagonist, especially seems like she was only included to connect every other character's stories. She doesn't accomplish anything, even though it's established that her powers are average at worst, barely ever takes initiative and once you think about you'll notice that her presence really change anything.\
The only other real character of note is Shun, a prodigy and quite straight-laced guy who seems to get along with everyone, while being a bit distant.\
He disappears during the show because...drama, I guess. That doesn't stop him from still talking with Saki during crucial moments to literally tell her what to do, however. Think Obi-Wan and Luke.\
I couldn't help but groan whenever Shun popped up later one, as I couldn't bring myself to care about him at all and fail to see how any viewer could really see anything in him.\
The characters as a whole don't seem to really grow from their experiences, which make all the character arcs leading up to the final arc mostly useless, save for a bit of lackluster foreshadowing here and there.\
-----\
Overall, I'd call this show a huge missed opportunity.\
I've found myself not caring about a lot of the episodes after the big exposition dump, since the final conflict is hinted at so obviously, which means the only reason to really watch the middle of this anime is if you really like the characters. The dynamics between characters don't really change massively, neither do the characters themselves. The point the anime tries to raise is incredibly stupid in this setting and did not need 25 episodes.\
In general, a good 8-10 episodes could probably be skipped and you'd only miss some very lame character moments and foreshadowing.\
I think I would've dropped this show and felt really insulted by the questions it tries to raise if I hadn't desperately wanted to learn every last bit of the setting.\
