                          \
    Story & tone: 10/10\
Shinsekai Yori is set one millennium into the future, in something that looks like a Utopia, and where every human possesses psychokinetic powers. The viewers do however understand that something isn’t quite right, from the very start of the series. \
The anime got a pretty slow paced plot, which helps it a lot when it comes to world building and adding a mysterious suspension. It’s a pretty mature show, which is hard for a lot of the typical anime watcher to enjoy. It’s doesn’t have a lot of action or fancy fighting, but rather world building and mature themes.\
The show challenges the\
          \
        viewer both morally and psychologically, and makes it believable. There are no good or bad in the real world, but rather different shades of gray and perspectives.\
Characters: 9/10\
The characters in Shinsekai Yori, doesn’t have as much personality as most fictional characters, but rather more realistic ones. We follow the main character, as she learns the truth in the same way as the viewers do. Most of the main cast can be seen as a medium, to explore the world of Shinsekai Yori. If the characters had too much personality, it would derive from the realism and the main aspect of this show, the world building. However, just like in the real world, there are some characters, with more personality and ambition than others.\
Production value (animation & audio): 7/10\
Shinsekai Yori got a pretty unique art style. It’s by no means very high quality, but it fits the tone of the show perfectly. It got creative designs for a plethora of different creatures, while making the humans characters have realistic, but varied character designs. The animation quality, do however vary, and it even had guest directors in 2 episodes. Animation quality is probably the weakest point of this anime.\
The voice acting fits the characters perfectly, and they never feel forced or inadequate while expressing emotions. When it comes to delivering an atmospheric environment, the music is spot on. With a combination of haunting, thrilling and somber music, it got a great combination of mesmerizing OST. There is no OP in this anime, but the ED delivers spot on, and help you calm down after a nerve wracking episode.\
Overall: 9/10\
Overall, the most important thing about Shinsekai Yori is still its world building, and it delivers spot on. It’s probably the most mature and interesting take, I’ve seen on the fantasy genre. While some people may find the first episodes slow, I personally loved the build up, and the payoff was even better. I’d recommend this show, if you’re a fan of more slow paced story and world building in anime, rather than your typical flashy fantasy show.\
