          \
        you. I've seen some pretty bad ratings but reading the reviews which explained them, It just felt like the viewers had given up on the series too soon without understanding what they were watching.\
Shin Sekai Yori is first and foremost a psychological anime which raises disturbing questions to its viewers. It is also targeted to a mature audience, it is important before bothering to watch it. If you're a 13 to 15 years-old, you may be a bit green to watch this not because of the images but rather because of its challenging content.\
Now in more details:\
Story: 10\
In an unknown time, we follow a group of kids in their journey to adulthood. They live in some sort of Utopian society but it soon appears that there's something very rotten underneath though neither you nor the kids know where exactly this feeling is coming from. It doesn't help that even the adults are forbidden to speak about certain subjects.\
About 4 episodes in, out main characters learn of certain truths which will be at the heart of their challenges ahead. \
I found it remarkable how even though most of the mysteries are explained early, the anime makes you change your mind about the disputable choices made by those who created this utopia on several occasions.\
I actually had to take a break from the series after 12 episodes since the series doesn't shy away from cruelty. Maybe I got too invested, but I had a hard time dealing with certain events portrayed and found it particularly hard on the children especially since at that point it was very difficult to understand why such hard choices and decisions had been made.\
Overall, the story's well crafted though I would have loved a couple of more episodes to make the transitions between the different time jumps smoother... But you can't have everything.\
Art: 8\
I really didn't like the character design at first, especially the overly big eyes which totally creeped me out combined with their very skinny bodies... But ultimately it does contribute to the general feeling of unease that transpires through the series. \
I'm also not too fond of the queercat's design. I actually found them pretty disgusting... It's interesting to note that Kiroumaru, although a queercat, has been given a more noble appearance closer to that of humans ( he's also taller than most adult humans when all the other queercats are smaller than 10 year-old children) . This however is not explained throughout the series.\
Overall the art is good, and although I'm not a fan, I've got to admit that it fits the disturbing atmosphere on the whole. It's also interesting how the world of humans is full of vivid colors while those of the queercats is always featured in caves and shadows.\
Sound: 9\
