    Reseña en Español al final...\
As always I will split this review in several points: Universe, Character Development, Plot Development and \"Animation, Music, Cast\"\
Universe: The utopian/dystopian universe in animes are not exactly my specialty, but I've seen quite a few stories which treats the same. Yet Shinsekai Yori originality overflows with a timeline (which although is not told in detail) of a series of tragedies that span more than 1000 years in order reach the present moment in history. The society that the author has created, how they live, and the past that they carry on their shoulders has been prepared in a great way\
          \
        in order to match with the development and the conclusion of events in the end of the story\
Character Development: It is perhaps the most developed point of the series. The anime focuses largely on the interaction of the 5 main characters (Saki, Satoru, Maria, Mamoru and Shun) as they discover the secrets hidden in their universe throughout the series. The utopian universe that has been created in the series, plus the mysterious atmosphere that is always in stories of small and eerie towns leads to psychological genres hues as the story moves on. Furthermore, while the story progresses it starting to show that these characters begin to relate to each other of the most bizarre ways (women with women, men with men) although this is due to the universe where events takes place.\
Plot Development: Divided in three distinct stages separated by time skips of a couple of years between each one. The events are narrated in past tense by the protagonist Saki as an adult that tells all significant events that occurred from her childhood to adulthood where the story ends. Although the beginning is a bit slow and incomprehensible, from chapter 4 onwards begins to understand some things and at least in my case starts to get interested in how it will end. And even as the story continues to enter in slow potholes, there is always that feeling of wanting to keep watching episodes\
Animation, Music and Cast: A-1 Pictures has always been known for their “all-in” bets with their mega-budgets and animation quality for their “Mainstream” anime, but it’s not the case in the series that are a bit more “hipster” and this happens with this anime, although quality is not bad, being a fantasy world needs a little more attention to detail in terms of CG. Nevertheless I still thought that has an average quality. In Regards of the OST I must say that it does not stand out a lot and that's good for the mystery of the story. Also it lacks of an Opening Song and my personal opinion is a con for this show. Because the Opening Song is an important part of the entire project promotion. Regarding VA’s, there isn’t a super cast, but the selection was correct for the 5 main characters. The best role was undoubtedly the veteran Yoshiko Sakakibara (Hellsing, Psycho-Pass) in the voice of Tomohiko Asahina\
Conclusions: I must emphasize that it is not an anime for everyone; it has elements that not play well with most of people. The universe where the story is developed is a society that homosexuality looks normal, and because of that, many people will run away from this anime. Yet if you are a tolerant viewer and you are looking an anime something innovative and out of the stereotype this is a good option, And more if you already like these genres. (I think so, since I'm not one of those xD)\
With nothing more to say, I turn down my pen (or rather my keyboard) for this week before telling you: Enjoy, Comment and Criticize I'm open to constructive criticism so that together we improve on this work. ^^\
